WEBVTT

00:05.092 --> 00:07.181
<i>Previously
on "New Amsterdam"...</i>

00:07.224 --> 00:10.053
I can--I can't be
who I want to be

00:10.097 --> 00:11.663
with you.

00:11.707 --> 00:13.013
[sighs]

00:13.056 --> 00:15.015
I think
I might have to crash here.

00:15.058 --> 00:16.277
Yeah, sure thing, sis.

00:16.320 --> 00:17.495
You're sober, Lauren.

00:17.539 --> 00:19.062
<i>You can't handle
that kind of temptation.</i>

00:19.106 --> 00:20.672
<i>What I can't handle
is guilt, okay?</i>

00:20.716 --> 00:22.500
<i>She's a mess because I left
her there with my mother.</i>

00:22.544 --> 00:25.155
You went from
Norman Rockwell to screaming.

00:25.199 --> 00:26.461
<i>Could've gone to jail.</i>

00:26.504 --> 00:28.158
No, we're not goin' fishing.
we're going home.

00:28.202 --> 00:29.464
You've been pestering me
for months!

00:29.507 --> 00:31.683
It sounds like
a textbook example

00:31.727 --> 00:34.121
of someone
with bipolar disorder.

00:34.164 --> 00:37.124
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:37.167 --> 00:38.168
<i>♪</i>

00:38.212 --> 00:40.040
[muted voice] Friends.

00:40.083 --> 00:41.128
[whispers] Friends.

00:41.171 --> 00:46.263
<i>♪</i>

00:46.307 --> 00:47.917
Move, move, move,
move, move, move.

00:47.960 --> 00:49.049
[all scream]

00:49.092 --> 00:50.050
Clear a path!

00:50.093 --> 00:52.400
<i>♪</i>

00:52.443 --> 00:54.315
Hey, you get Max's page?

00:54.358 --> 00:55.272
You only got one?

00:55.316 --> 00:57.796
<i>♪</i>

00:57.840 --> 01:00.190
- What do three 911s mean?
- Can't be anything good.

01:00.234 --> 01:02.671
Oh, excuse me,
excuse me, coming through!

01:02.714 --> 01:04.629
- Did he page everyone?
- Yes, this must be bad.

01:04.673 --> 01:06.631
- Make a damn hole!
- Move aside, please.

01:06.675 --> 01:08.111
Move. Move. Move.

01:08.155 --> 01:09.504
Max, what's wrong?

01:09.547 --> 01:10.809
- What's the emergency?
- What is it?

01:10.853 --> 01:12.376
Is everything okay
with the hospital?

01:12.420 --> 01:13.725
Is it a mass casualty?

01:13.769 --> 01:14.944
Whoa, whoa, whoa.

01:14.987 --> 01:16.163
- Tell me Veronica's not back.
- Hold on.

01:16.206 --> 01:17.686
Just take a seat.
All right?

01:17.729 --> 01:19.470
Come on in.
Why don't you take a breath?

01:19.514 --> 01:22.256
In fact, why don't we all take
a nice, deep breath with me?

01:22.299 --> 01:23.692
Ready? In...

01:23.735 --> 01:25.215
[all inhale]

01:25.259 --> 01:27.130
And out.
[all exhale]

01:27.174 --> 01:28.523
There we go.
Doesn't that feel better?

01:28.566 --> 01:30.742
Yeah?
Okay, now that we are

01:30.786 --> 01:34.137
nice and relaxed,
I have some bad news.

01:34.181 --> 01:36.139
You are all
in critical condition.

01:36.183 --> 01:38.141
What--what does that mean, exactly?

01:38.185 --> 01:40.100
Well, it means that morale
for doctors

01:40.143 --> 01:41.492
is at an all-time low.

01:41.536 --> 01:42.841
You gotta be kiddin' me, Max.

01:42.885 --> 01:44.147
Uh, not kidding.

01:44.191 --> 01:46.410
Burnout and turnover
are at an all-time high,

01:46.454 --> 01:48.020
and if it continues
at this pace,

01:48.064 --> 01:50.153
we're not gonna have enough
staff to keep the doors open.

01:50.197 --> 01:51.894
Yeah, you made this sound
like it was a real emergency.

01:51.937 --> 01:53.896
This is a real emergency.

01:53.939 --> 01:56.290
Your hours are too long.
Your downtime is too short,

01:56.333 --> 01:57.508
and you don't have
the mental space

01:57.552 --> 01:59.119
to take care of yourselves.

01:59.162 --> 02:00.424
And if you can't do that,

02:00.468 --> 02:02.383
how are you gonna
take care of your patients?

02:02.426 --> 02:04.515
[people whispering]
- [coughing]

02:06.169 --> 02:07.649
I got some surgeries
to attend to.

02:07.692 --> 02:09.433
Well, actually, you don't,
because I took the liberty

02:09.477 --> 02:11.827
of clearing
your entire schedule.

02:14.090 --> 02:17.093
In fact, nobody in this room

02:17.137 --> 02:20.227
has anything urgent
to do today,

02:20.270 --> 02:24.274
because today, your one
and only patient is you.

02:24.318 --> 02:26.755
<i>[upbeat music]</i>

02:26.798 --> 02:28.322
<i>♪</i>

02:28.365 --> 02:30.976
I hope everyone gets as excited
as Dr. Lauren Bloom here.

02:31.020 --> 02:32.369
Yes, question.
Elizabeth?

02:32.413 --> 02:34.371
- "No."
- Okay, not really a question,

02:34.415 --> 02:35.851
but, uh, the answer is yes.

02:35.894 --> 02:38.201
We are all going to prioritize
the health issues

02:38.245 --> 02:39.681
that we have been putting off,

02:39.724 --> 02:42.205
because we're either
too busy or too tired.

02:42.249 --> 02:44.512
Now say it with me.
- Please don't.

02:44.555 --> 02:45.817
We can do it.
Ready?

02:45.861 --> 02:48.298
Doctors, heal thyself!

02:48.342 --> 02:50.344
Oh, God.
[all muttering]

02:50.387 --> 02:51.997
[laughs] Ooh.

02:52.041 --> 02:56.001
<i>♪</i>

02:56.045 --> 02:58.830
Ooh, I think
the New Amsterdam newsletter

02:58.874 --> 03:00.832
has found its centerfold.

03:00.876 --> 03:02.486
Pretty sure you're not
allowed to say stuff

03:02.530 --> 03:05.010
like that anymore.
- Yeah.

03:05.054 --> 03:06.229
Let me.

03:06.273 --> 03:08.884
[monitor beeping]

03:09.841 --> 03:13.149
This latest Max plan is such
a ridiculous waste of time.

03:13.193 --> 03:14.498
Suck it up.
I just got my first

03:14.542 --> 03:16.239
mammogram in three years.

03:16.283 --> 03:17.675
It had been weighing
on my mind,

03:17.719 --> 03:19.721
but I had no time
to do anything about it.

03:19.764 --> 03:21.940
- And?
- I'm in perfect health,

03:21.984 --> 03:23.377
and you'll be too.

03:29.600 --> 03:32.168
What?

03:32.212 --> 03:34.866
If this is a bit,
it's not funny.

03:34.910 --> 03:38.000
You--you have a short
PR interval and a delta wave

03:38.043 --> 03:39.697
at onset of the QRS complex.

03:39.741 --> 03:41.438
Are you suggesting
pre-excitation syndrome?

03:41.482 --> 03:45.312
No, I am saying it flat-out.

03:45.355 --> 03:47.923
You have
Wolf-Parkinson-White Syndrome.

03:48.837 --> 03:51.056
I'm fitting you in for
a catheter ablation at 4:00.

03:51.100 --> 03:52.580
[sighs]

03:52.623 --> 03:54.146
Nah.

03:54.190 --> 03:57.585
Floyd, you know the risks
of a re-entrant tachycardia.

03:57.628 --> 03:59.891
What I do know is that
they're not as immediate

03:59.935 --> 04:02.807
as the risk posed to my five
patients I had scheduled today.

04:02.851 --> 04:06.637
Now, I did my part
for Max's stupid plan.

04:06.681 --> 04:07.899
I'm gonna go tend to them.

04:07.943 --> 04:09.249
I'll deal with this
on my next day off.

04:09.292 --> 04:10.554
Oh, when is that?

04:12.643 --> 04:15.951
Yeah, I'll see you at 4:00,
hot stuff.

04:15.994 --> 04:18.388
<i>♪</i>

04:18.432 --> 04:20.129
So it's so nice to
finally meet you

04:20.172 --> 04:21.870
in the flesh, Ronel, you know?

04:21.913 --> 04:23.785
Not that our emoji-ladened
chats on the app

04:23.828 --> 04:24.873
haven't been fun.

04:24.916 --> 04:26.309
Cowboy hat, cowboy hat, fireworks.

04:26.353 --> 04:27.745
[laughs]

04:27.789 --> 04:30.487
Uh, spaceship,
pretzel, sunglasses.

04:33.708 --> 04:36.885
You've always been so busy,
and now you're suddenly free?

04:36.928 --> 04:39.496
- Yeah.
- Did you get fired?

04:39.540 --> 04:42.586
[laughs] No, no--
not that I know of, anyway.

04:42.630 --> 04:44.284
No, no, I'm as shocked
as you are.

04:44.327 --> 04:45.763
You know, my boss he, uh--

04:45.807 --> 04:47.722
he insisted that all of us
take a health day--

04:47.765 --> 04:48.940
you know, out of the blue.

04:48.984 --> 04:50.420
Initially,
I was really resentful,

04:50.464 --> 04:52.074
but then I realized that,
like, it had been so long

04:52.117 --> 04:54.598
since I had actual
human-to-human contact

04:54.642 --> 04:57.122
outside of work that I thought

04:57.166 --> 04:59.951
this was the most healthy thing
I could do.

04:59.995 --> 05:01.039
So you wanna hit it?

05:01.083 --> 05:02.389
What--do I wanna hit it?

05:05.566 --> 05:08.351
Uh...
[laughs nervously]

05:08.395 --> 05:09.787
Yeah, I mean, I'd love--
I'd love to hit it.

05:09.831 --> 05:11.354
But you know,
I heard that this place

05:11.398 --> 05:12.790
has a wonderful tarte Tatin

05:12.834 --> 05:14.705
that's apparently
somethin' else.

05:14.749 --> 05:19.971
It's nothing compared
to what I'd like to give you.

05:20.015 --> 05:21.146
Doctor's orders, right?

05:21.190 --> 05:24.846
<i>♪</i>

05:24.889 --> 05:26.500
[clears throat]
'Scuse me.

05:26.543 --> 05:27.675
Check, please.

05:29.590 --> 05:31.287
I--so, sorry--

05:31.331 --> 05:33.158
so, so sorry.

05:33.202 --> 05:34.986
Okay, spoiler alert.

05:35.030 --> 05:37.772
This one is going to be
clean as a whistle.

05:37.815 --> 05:39.382
I mean pristine.

05:39.426 --> 05:41.993
You seem real proud
of this sample.

05:42.037 --> 05:43.908
Oh, I am, yeah.

05:43.952 --> 05:46.041
You have any idea
how hard it is staying sober,

05:46.084 --> 05:48.826
living with my sister?
- Can't say I do.

05:48.870 --> 05:52.003
Well, she wakes up
to tequila shots.

05:52.047 --> 05:54.963
Yeah, her apartment
is like one big pharmacy.

05:55.006 --> 05:56.486
Essentially,
the whole thing is, like,

05:56.530 --> 05:58.923
one big trigger for me.

05:58.967 --> 06:02.492
BP's good.
Now let's check your weight.

06:02.536 --> 06:04.842
I guess I'd be lying
if I said it hadn't

06:04.886 --> 06:08.672
tested my sobriety,
but she needs me, you know?

06:08.716 --> 06:10.674
- Mm-hmm.
- What does it cost me, right--

06:10.718 --> 06:13.547
to finally be there for her?

06:13.590 --> 06:15.157
It looks like
you lost five pounds.

06:15.200 --> 06:16.419
Oh.

06:16.463 --> 06:18.073
Why, thank you, doctor.

06:18.116 --> 06:20.249
You need to stop
taking your Adderall.

06:20.292 --> 06:21.642
I'm sorry, what?

06:21.685 --> 06:23.644
You're underweight,
and the protocol is clear.

06:23.687 --> 06:25.733
So I can't refill
your prescription,

06:25.776 --> 06:28.953
and you'll have to hand over
any pills you have.

06:28.997 --> 06:31.434
So you just want me
to quit cold turkey?

06:31.478 --> 06:34.132
I'm just following
the protocols.

06:34.176 --> 06:36.744
Yeah, but you're not
gonna hold me to that.

06:36.787 --> 06:38.963
You know that this
is a class of medication

06:39.007 --> 06:40.704
that makes it harder
to maintain weight,

06:40.748 --> 06:42.445
and yours is dangerously low.

06:49.539 --> 06:52.455
You know,
if I don't get my meds...

06:52.499 --> 06:54.239
you know what happens.

06:54.283 --> 06:55.632
My hands are tied here.

06:55.676 --> 06:58.722
I get irritable,
anxious, distracted.

06:58.766 --> 07:01.551
I can't focus.
- Lauren...

07:01.595 --> 07:02.944
the bottle.

07:02.987 --> 07:04.946
<i>[tense music]</i>

07:04.989 --> 07:05.990
<i>♪</i>

07:06.034 --> 07:07.427
I run
an emergency department.

07:07.470 --> 07:08.689
I mean, I can't do that

07:08.732 --> 07:11.039
if I, myself, am in a state
of emergency.

07:11.082 --> 07:16.087
<i>♪</i>

07:16.131 --> 07:18.263
Look, come back at the end
of the week

07:18.307 --> 07:19.569
for another weigh-in.

07:19.613 --> 07:20.962
If you put on the weight,

07:21.005 --> 07:23.007
I'm happy to give you
your pills back.

07:23.051 --> 07:24.792
<i>♪</i>

07:24.835 --> 07:25.967
Okay.

07:26.010 --> 07:30.711
<i>♪</i>

07:30.754 --> 07:32.277
Just take
the rest of the week off.

07:32.321 --> 07:34.062
I'm perfectly capable
of running the E.D.

07:34.105 --> 07:35.890
if you recall.
- Actually, as I recall,

07:35.933 --> 07:37.761
you needed me to do it.
- Wow, already,

07:37.805 --> 07:38.936
the moodiness is upon us.
That was fast.

07:38.980 --> 07:40.285
No, it's just
a couple of pounds.

07:40.329 --> 07:41.461
I mean, I'm gonna have it
handled by lunchtime,

07:41.504 --> 07:42.374
'cause I got a plan--
right there.

07:42.418 --> 07:43.854
See?

07:43.898 --> 07:47.162
All right, let's do this!
- I've never been so inspired.

07:47.205 --> 07:48.642
- What do we got?
- Displaced patient,

07:48.685 --> 07:50.121
32 weeks gestation
and contracting.

07:50.165 --> 07:51.732
Uh, why didn't we send her
up to the OB?

07:51.775 --> 07:53.690
I did.
They sent her back--no room.

07:53.734 --> 07:57.085
Oh, the cafeteria served
the eggplant parm again?

07:57.128 --> 07:59.130
Like clockwork.
Every time, we get flooded

07:59.174 --> 08:01.872
with patients in labor.
- The ergots are gonna get ya.

08:03.439 --> 08:05.267
Hi, Aria.
I'm Dr. Bloom.

08:05.310 --> 08:09.314
So your contractions are
what we call Braxton-Hicks.

08:09.358 --> 08:10.794
It's actually fake labor,

08:10.838 --> 08:12.187
but it's nothing
to stress over.

08:12.230 --> 08:13.928
My husband's in Cleveland.
Should he fly back?

08:13.971 --> 08:15.538
No, no.
There is no need

08:15.582 --> 08:16.974
to disrupt his day, okay?

08:17.018 --> 08:18.933
What you need
is rest and peace.

08:18.976 --> 08:21.718
So I'm just gonna move you
to a quieter part of the E.D.

08:21.762 --> 08:23.807
where you can relax, okay?

08:23.851 --> 08:26.897
I'll be right back to check
on you in just a moment.

08:26.941 --> 08:29.944
All right, who's got grub?

08:29.987 --> 08:32.468
I was gonna eat that one.

08:32.512 --> 08:33.556
With that,
ladies and gentlemen,

08:33.600 --> 08:35.384
we coast right into aggression.

08:35.427 --> 08:38.430
Closed for the day, good.

08:38.474 --> 08:39.475
Closed.

08:39.519 --> 08:41.346
Closed, excellent.

08:41.390 --> 08:44.001
Closed. Great.

08:44.045 --> 08:45.437
Oh, hey.

08:45.481 --> 08:47.570
Sorry to micromanage.
I'm just, uh, goin' around,

08:47.614 --> 08:48.789
checkin' in to see how people

08:48.832 --> 08:50.399
are doing
with today's mandate, so...

08:50.442 --> 08:52.662
"Me?
Oh, well, uh, you know,

08:52.706 --> 08:55.839
"I just took a power nap.
[groans]

08:55.883 --> 08:58.407
That was--wow.
Best five minutes of my day."

08:58.450 --> 09:01.845
Huh, yeah, naps are good,
but I was kind of looking

09:01.889 --> 09:04.805
for more of a designated,
real self-care day--

09:04.848 --> 09:07.503
you know,
appointments and procedures,

09:07.547 --> 09:09.331
that kind of thing.
Is there anything you've been

09:09.374 --> 09:10.550
letting fall by the wayside?

09:10.593 --> 09:12.029
- Mm-mm.
- "Nope."

09:12.073 --> 09:14.945
Come on.
Surely there's something.

09:17.905 --> 09:19.776
What?
- Uh...

09:19.820 --> 09:21.604
"Uh," what?
What?

09:21.648 --> 09:24.868
What was that?
That was something.

09:24.912 --> 09:27.044
That's "Him--him.
Tell--tell him."

09:27.088 --> 09:30.482
That means, "Tell him."
I know what that means.

09:30.526 --> 09:31.614
Tell me.

09:31.658 --> 09:32.920
What?

09:35.096 --> 09:36.880
He's right.

09:36.924 --> 09:39.622
- Okay.
- "I need surgery.

09:39.666 --> 09:41.581
But it's really
not a big deal."

09:41.624 --> 09:42.799
Mm.

09:42.843 --> 09:45.759
<i>[light suspenseful music]</i>

09:45.802 --> 09:47.630
<i>♪</i>

09:47.674 --> 09:50.894
Uh, but see the thing is,
surgery is kind of a big deal,

09:50.938 --> 09:53.723
because it's surgery.
So what is it?

09:53.767 --> 09:54.768
[whispers] I have--

09:54.811 --> 09:55.899
"I have
carpal tunnel syndrome."

09:55.943 --> 09:59.076
Well--well,
that's fixable, right?

09:59.120 --> 10:02.471
"Yes, sure.
Uh, physical therapy,

10:02.514 --> 10:05.082
"acupuncture,
icing your wrists twice a day,

10:05.126 --> 10:08.651
"steroid shots and all that.
It did not work.

10:08.695 --> 10:11.349
Now surgery
is the only option."

10:13.090 --> 10:15.832
Well, uh, so you--
you get it.

10:15.876 --> 10:18.748
- [laughs]
- "It is my hands, Max.

10:18.792 --> 10:20.837
"Even if everything
goes perfectly,

10:20.881 --> 10:23.274
I wouldn't be able
to use my hands for weeks."

10:23.318 --> 10:24.928
<i>♪</i>

10:24.972 --> 10:27.452
- Well, but you--
- Stay!

10:27.496 --> 10:29.193
Just--

10:29.237 --> 10:31.892
<i>♪</i>

10:35.417 --> 10:38.115
[groans]
[door creaks]

10:39.247 --> 10:41.075
Ignatius,

10:41.118 --> 10:43.599
you look positively trounced,

10:43.643 --> 10:45.645
though, not necessarily
in a bad way.

10:45.688 --> 10:47.821
Hello, Dorian.
It's nice to see you.

10:47.864 --> 10:49.692
You know, you would think
that being a psychiatrist,

10:49.736 --> 10:51.259
you would know
a little more about tact--

10:51.302 --> 10:52.260
you know,
especially after practicing

10:52.303 --> 10:53.478
for what, 900 years now?

10:53.522 --> 10:54.566
Ouch.

10:56.307 --> 10:57.439
[under breath] I'm sorry.

10:57.482 --> 10:59.136
Dorian.
Dorian, I'm sorry.

10:59.180 --> 11:02.705
Hey, I just--it's just--

11:02.749 --> 11:04.315
it's us.

11:04.359 --> 11:07.362
- Psychiatrists?
- No, gay people.

11:07.405 --> 11:09.712
Why is our culture like this?
- I completely agree.

11:09.756 --> 11:12.454
I say this Gaga person
is no Streisand,

11:12.497 --> 11:13.934
and I don't care who knows.

11:13.977 --> 11:16.371
I am talking about
our obsession with sex, Dorian.

11:16.414 --> 11:17.677
You know on some
of these dating apps,

11:17.720 --> 11:19.287
they don't even want
a picture of your face?

11:19.330 --> 11:20.897
- That's awful.
- Yeah!

11:20.941 --> 11:22.638
What did you say
the name of that one was?

11:22.682 --> 11:25.772
Of course, gosh.
It's dehumanizing, you know?

11:25.815 --> 11:27.948
The last time I was
in the dating pool,

11:27.991 --> 11:30.341
which was pre-internet,
you had to talk to someone

11:30.385 --> 11:31.865
before you just took 'em home.

11:31.908 --> 11:34.128
Yes, that's what gay clubs
have all been famous for--

11:34.171 --> 11:35.520
talking.
- Look, I'm just saying

11:35.564 --> 11:37.740
that I was shocked
at how bad it is out there.

11:37.784 --> 11:39.437
That's all.

11:39.481 --> 11:42.353
In my day,
the best I could hope for

11:42.397 --> 11:44.747
was a furtive meeting
in a park,

11:44.791 --> 11:47.271
while keeping my fingers
crossed that no vice cops

11:47.315 --> 11:48.664
were watching.
- Right.

11:48.708 --> 11:52.712
Talking wasn't exactly
at a premium then either.

11:52.755 --> 11:55.845
But what this sounds like,
to my experienced ears,

11:55.889 --> 11:59.283
is a guy complaining
after a bad date.

11:59.327 --> 12:02.678
No, no, wrong, completely.

12:04.375 --> 12:06.551
